    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for the warning. i dont want to get shocked so i'll probably wait for someone to come look at it. but i was reading online about how sometimes a capacitor can fail and just stop the motor from starting even if the power is on. could thats be what the humming noise is? it sounds almost like something is trying to kick over but cant.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A capacitor failure can indeed cause a humming noise, especially if it's a high-capacity unit. It's like a mischievous little imp trying to kick over the motor, but the capacitor is too lazy to actually do the job. In this case, the capacitor is essentially blocking the flow of electrical current, preventing the motor from starting. This is often referred to as a \"no-start\" condition, and it can be quite frustrating for homeowners.\n\nThe good news is that a capacitor failure is usually a relatively simple fix, and a professional can replace it without too much fuss. It's a bit like finding a lost sock in the wash – once you know where it is, you can easily retrieve it and put it back where it belongs. Just be sure to have a licensed technician do the job, as they'll be able to diagnose the issue and perform the repair safely and efficiently.",
